{
  "A continental polar (cP) air mass is:": "",
  "Cold and dry": "",
  "Warm and moist": "",
  "Cold and moist": "",
  "Warm and dry": "",
  "Continental polar air masses form over cold land areas like Canada and Siberia, where they acquire cold temperatures from the frigid surface and remain dry because continental sources lack significant moisture.": "",
  "A maritime tropical (mT) air mass is:": "",
  "Maritime tropical air masses form over warm ocean areas like the Gulf of Mexico and the tropical Atlantic, where they absorb heat and moisture from the warm water surface.": "",
  "When a cold front passes through, you typically experience:": "",
  "Sharp temperature drop, heavy but brief precipitation, then clearing skies": "",
  "Gradual warming over several days": "",
  "No noticeable weather changes": "",
  "Prolonged light rain lasting several days": "",
  "Cold fronts move quickly and force warm air upward abruptly, producing intense but short-lived precipitation along a narrow band, followed by a sharp drop in temperature and clearing skies as the cold air mass moves in.": "",
  "Warm fronts typically produce _____ precipitation.": "",
  "Light to moderate, steady, and prolonged": "",
  "Only severe thunderstorms": "",
  "No precipitation at all": "",
  "Heavy, brief": "",
  "Warm fronts advance slowly and the warm air gradually rides up over the retreating cold air mass along a gentle slope, producing a wide area of light to moderate, steady precipitation that can last for hours or days.": "",
  "On a weather map, cold fronts are shown with:": "",
  "Red semicircles": "",
  "Blue triangles pointing in the direction of movement": "",
  "Green arrows": "",
  "Yellow dots along the boundary": "",
  "Cold fronts are depicted on weather maps as blue lines with triangular barbs (pips) pointing in the direction the front is moving, while warm fronts use red lines with semicircles.": "",
  "Low pressure systems rotate _____ in the Northern Hemisphere.": "",
  "They do not rotate": "",
  "Counterclockwise": "",
  "Clockwise": "",
  "In random directions": "",
  "Due to the Coriolis effect caused by Earth's rotation, low pressure systems (cyclones) rotate counterclockwise in the Northern Hemisphere and clockwise in the Southern Hemisphere.": "",
  "High pressure systems are generally associated with:": "",
  "Storms and heavy rain": "",
  "Hurricanes": "",
  "Clear skies and fair weather": "",
  "Tornadoes": "",
  "High pressure systems feature sinking air that warms as it descends, suppressing cloud formation and producing clear skies, calm winds, and generally fair weather conditions.": "",
  "The Coriolis effect causes moving air to deflect due to:": "",
  "Differences in wind speed": "",
  "Temperature differences between air masses": "",
  "Earth's rotation": "",
  "Pressure differences alone": "",
  "The Coriolis effect is an apparent deflection of moving objects (including air) caused by Earth's rotation, deflecting them to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere.": "",
  "Wind blows from _____ pressure areas to _____ pressure areas.": "",
  "Low to high": "",
  "North to south always": "",
  "East to west always": "",
  "High to low": "",
  "Air naturally flows from areas of higher pressure toward areas of lower pressure due to the pressure gradient force, just as water flows downhill from high elevation to low elevation.": "",
  "Mid-latitude cyclones typically move across North America from:": "",
  "East to west": "",
  "West to east": "",
  "South to north": "",
  "North to south": "",
  "Mid-latitude cyclones are carried across North America from west to east by the prevailing westerlies, the dominant wind pattern in the mid-latitudes between approximately 30 and 60 degrees latitude.": "",
  "What is an occluded front?": "",
  "A front that forms when a faster cold front overtakes a warm front, lifting the warm air completely off the surface": "",
  "A front that remains stationary for weeks at a time": "",
  "A front that forms only over the ocean": "",
  "A front that forms when two warm air masses merge": "",
  "An occluded front forms when a fast-moving cold front catches up to and overtakes a slower-moving warm front, forcing the warm air mass entirely off the ground surface and often signaling that a mid-latitude cyclone is weakening.": "",
  "What is a stationary front?": "",
  "A front found only in the stratosphere": "",
  "A permanent front located at the equator": "",
  "A boundary between two air masses where neither air mass is advancing significantly": "",
  "A front that moves at extremely high speeds": "",
  "A stationary front occurs when the boundary between two air masses stalls because neither has enough force to advance over the other, often producing prolonged cloudiness and precipitation over the same area for days.": "",
  "What is the pressure gradient force?": "",
  "The force of friction between air and the ground surface": "",
  "The centripetal force acting on air in rotating storms": "",
  "The gravitational pull that keeps the atmosphere attached to Earth": "",
  "The force that drives air from areas of high pressure to areas of low pressure": "",
  "The pressure gradient force is the fundamental driving force of wind, pushing air from regions of higher atmospheric pressure toward regions of lower pressure, with the strength of the force proportional to the difference in pressure over a given distance.": "",
  "What does convergence mean in meteorology?": "",
  "Air moving horizontally at a constant speed": "",
  "Air spreading outward from a central point": "",
  "Air descending from the upper atmosphere to the surface": "",
  "Air flowing inward toward a central area, forcing air upward": "",
  "Convergence occurs in low pressure systems where surface air flows inward toward the center from all directions, and since it cannot pile up at the surface, it is forced upward, leading to cloud formation and precipitation.": "",
  "What is the dew point temperature?": "",
  "The temperature at which all water evaporates from the air": "",
  "The temperature at which air becomes saturated and water vapor begins to condense": "",
  "The temperature at which rain stops falling": "",
  "The maximum temperature reached during the day": "",
  "The dew point is the temperature to which air must be cooled (at constant pressure and moisture content) to become saturated, at which point water vapor begins to condense into liquid water, forming dew, fog, or clouds.": "",
  "What does an isobar represent on a weather map?": "",
  "A line showing the path of a storm": "",
  "A line connecting points of equal humidity": "",
  "A line connecting points of equal atmospheric pressure": "",
  "A line connecting points of equal temperature": "",
  "Isobars are lines drawn on weather maps connecting points of equal atmospheric pressure, and their spacing indicates wind speed: closely spaced isobars indicate a steep pressure gradient and stronger winds.": "",
  "What is a barometer?": "",
  "An instrument that measures atmospheric pressure": "",
  "An instrument that measures humidity": "",
  "An instrument that measures wind speed": "",
  "An instrument that measures temperature": "",
  "A barometer is a scientific instrument used to measure atmospheric pressure, and falling barometric pressure often indicates approaching storms while rising pressure typically signals improving weather conditions.": "",
  "What is frontal lifting?": "",
  "The upward movement of air caused by mountain terrain": "",
  "The process where warm air is forced upward over denser cold air when two air masses of different temperatures meet": "",
  "The rising of air caused by solar heating of the ground": "",
  "The process of warm air sinking below cold air at a front": "",
  "Frontal lifting occurs when warm and cold air masses collide, and the less dense warm air is forced to rise over the denser cold air, cooling as it ascends and often producing clouds and precipitation along the frontal boundary.": "",
  "What is divergence in the context of high pressure systems?": "",
  "Air flowing inward toward the center of the system": "",
  "Air sinking at the center and spreading outward from the system at the surface": "",
  "The breakup of a storm system into smaller cells": "",
  "Air rising rapidly to form cumulonimbus clouds": "",
  "In high pressure systems, air subsides (sinks) from aloft and spreads outward at the surface in a pattern called divergence, which is why high pressure areas are associated with clear, dry weather rather than cloud formation.": "",
  "What is an air mass?": "",
  "A large body of air with relatively uniform temperature and moisture characteristics acquired from its source region": "",
  "A pocket of turbulence within a thunderstorm": "",
  "A narrow band of strong wind in the upper atmosphere": "",
  "The total weight of the atmosphere above a given location": "",
  "An air mass is a large volume of air (often covering thousands of square kilometers) that has relatively uniform temperature and humidity throughout, having acquired these properties from the surface of its source region over time.": "",
  "A weather map shows a large 'L' symbol with tightly packed isobars approaching your city from the west. Based on this information, you should expect:": "",
  "Fog formation due to high pressure settling over the area": "",
  "Strong winds and precipitation as the intense low pressure system with a steep pressure gradient arrives": "",
  "Clear and calm conditions for the next several days": "",
  "Light winds with gradually increasing temperatures": "",
  "A low pressure system with tightly packed isobars indicates a steep pressure gradient, which produces strong winds, while the rising air in the low pressure center creates clouds and precipitation, making for stormy conditions.": "",
  "In the spring, a severe thunderstorm outbreak occurs across the central United States when warm, moist Gulf air collides with a mass of cold, dry Canadian air. This situation represents the collision of which air mass types?": "",
  "Continental tropical (cT) and maritime polar (mP)": "",
  "Maritime polar (mP) and continental tropical (cT)": "",
  "Continental polar (cP) and continental arctic (cA)": "",
  "Maritime tropical (mT) and continental polar (cP)": "",
  "Severe weather in the central US frequently results from maritime tropical (mT) air from the Gulf of Mexico colliding with continental polar (cP) air from Canada, creating strong temperature and moisture contrasts along the frontal boundary.": "",
  "A pilot flying from Los Angeles to New York notices strong headwinds that significantly slow the aircraft's ground speed. On the return trip, the same winds provide a strong tailwind. These winds are most likely:": "",
  "Polar easterlies descending from the Arctic": "",
  "The prevailing westerlies that carry weather systems from west to east across the mid-latitudes": "",
  "Trade winds blowing from east to west near the equator": "",
  "Sea breezes caused by differential heating of land and ocean": "",
  "The prevailing westerlies are the dominant wind pattern at mid-latitudes (30-60 degrees), blowing from west to east, which creates headwinds for westbound flights and tailwinds for eastbound flights, affecting flight times by up to an hour.": "",
  "A barometer reading drops rapidly from 1020 mb to 995 mb over six hours. Based on this observation, a meteorologist would most likely forecast:": "",
  "The approach of a strong storm system with increasing winds and precipitation": "",
  "Dense fog forming over the next few hours": "",
  "An extended period of fair weather and light winds": "",
  "Clear skies and rising temperatures": "",
  "A rapidly falling barometer indicates a strong low pressure system is approaching, and the 25 mb drop in just six hours represents a very steep pressure gradient that would bring strong winds, heavy precipitation, and potentially severe weather.": "",
  "A farmer in the Midwest notices that after several days of overcast skies and light drizzle, the precipitation suddenly becomes heavy, temperatures drop sharply, and the skies clear within a few hours. This sequence most likely indicates:": "",
  "A high pressure system brought the precipitation before clearing": "",
  "A warm front passed through followed by a tropical storm": "",
  "A stationary front lifted and dissipated": "",
  "A cold front passed through, replacing the warm air that had been producing the steady drizzle": "",
  "The initial days of steady light rain are typical of a warm front or warm sector, and the abrupt shift to heavy rain, rapid temperature drop, and quick clearing is the classic signature of a cold front passage pushing through the area.": "",
  "A meteorologist observes that a mid-latitude cyclone over the Great Lakes has an occluded front forming near its center. This most likely indicates that the storm is:": "",
  "Transitioning into a tropical cyclone": "",
  "Being strengthened by a high pressure system to its east": "",
  "Just beginning to develop and will intensify significantly": "",
  "Reaching its mature or weakening stage as the cold front has caught up to the warm front": "",
  "Occlusion occurs when the faster-moving cold front catches up to the warm front, lifting the warm air sector entirely off the surface, and this typically signals that the cyclone is entering its mature or dissipating phase.": "",
  "Two cities are at the same latitude, but City A is at the center of a persistent high pressure system while City B is under a low pressure system. Compared to City B, City A most likely has:": "",
  "Clearer skies, lighter winds, and drier conditions due to sinking air suppressing cloud formation": "",
  "More cloud cover and heavier precipitation": "",
  "Stronger surface winds due to the steep pressure gradient at its center": "",
  "Frequent severe thunderstorms from rising warm air": "",
  "High pressure systems feature subsiding (sinking) air at their center, which warms as it descends and suppresses cloud formation, producing clear skies, calm winds, and dry conditions compared to the rising air, clouds, and precipitation of a low pressure system.": "",
  "During a hurricane in the Northern Hemisphere, a weather observer on the coast notices winds initially blowing from the north. After the eye passes over, the winds shift to blowing from the south. This reversal occurs because:": "",
  "The Coriolis effect reverses during the calm eye of the storm": "",
  "The counterclockwise rotation of the hurricane means winds on opposite sides of the eye blow in opposite directions": "",
  "The hurricane changed direction during the eye passage": "",
  "The high pressure in the eye pushes winds outward in all directions": "",
  "Because hurricanes in the Northern Hemisphere rotate counterclockwise, a location on the east side of the eye experiences northerly winds as the storm approaches, and then southerly winds as the eye passes and the opposite side of the storm arrives.": "",
